  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Agreements\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide framework for national anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n\n2. Legal Harmonization\n- Countries align domestic legislation with international standards\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Uniform reporting and compliance requirements\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n\n3. Information Sharing\n- Cross-border cooperation between financial intelligence units\n- Collaborative investigation and prosecution of money laundering\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n\n4. Regulatory Compliance\n- Banks and financial institutions must follow international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International banking and financial networks\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Sanctions for non-compliance\n- International monitoring and evaluation\n- Peer review processes\n- Potential economic consequences for weak AML frameworks\n\n6. Technological Adaptation\n- Addressing digital currency and cryptocurrency challenges\n- Developing consistent regulatory approaches\n- Tracking emerging financial technologies\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered approach to combating money laundering globally.",
